 pencil. When the market recovered, his fortunes were greatly increased — he had never speculated in his life, so he had capital ready when others were ruined."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Bailed Republicans from Tammany jails every Election Day","body":"An ardent Republican since the birth of the party, James took every Election Day off. After voting, he went jail to jail across New York, bailing out any Republicans who had been locked up by corrupt Tammany Hall forces after being challenged at the polls."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"Tithed ten percent of his income, every year","body":"Throughout his career James gave at least ten percent of his income to charity. He funded Talcott Hall at Oberlin College (1887), an arboretum at Mount Holyoke, a library in West Hartford, and a hospital in China. With Dwight L."},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"Died at Lake Mohonk's peace community in 1916","body":"James was a frequent speaker at the Lake Mohonk Conferences on International Arbitration, the peace and Native rights gatherings convened by the Smiley brothers from 1883 onward. He died at Lake Mohonk Mountain House on August 21, 1916, age eighty-one, in the community where he had spoken on peace for decades."}],"bio":{"display_name":"James Talcott","first_name":"James","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777579998/850_James_Talcott_ipbmgm.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. Cloudinary."},"military_service":[],"slug":"james-talcott-1835"},"T01463":{"id":"T01463","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"gender":"male","birth":{"year":1866,"month":9,"day":14,"city":"West Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1944,"month":2,"day":6,"city":"Manhattan","county":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM112","plot_notes":"Woodlawn Cemetery, Bronx 