ation from a merchandise-handling firm into a capital-lending institution. From 1926 to 1941, sales grew from $17 million to $103 million, guiding the company through the Depression without debt."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"Raised $400,000 for America's first Black college","body":"As trustee of Lincoln University — the nation's first degree-granting historically Black college and university — Talcott headed a $400,000 fundraising campaign in 1934 for a new library, dining hall, gymnasium, and assembly area. He also endowed the J. Frederick Talcott Award, once considered the nation's highest honor for etching in the United States."}],"sources":[{"label":"Wikipedia — James Frederick Talcott","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Frederick_Talcott"},{"label":"J. Frederick Talcott obituary — New York Times, Feb 1944"}],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"title":"Deacon","first_name":"James","middle_name":"Frederick","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"nickname":"J. Frederick","display_name":"Deacon James Frederick Talcott","photo_url":"https://images.findagrave.com/photos/2017/171/180587173_1498074668.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. FindAGrave."},"military_service":[],"slug":"james-talcott-1866"},"I00192":{"id":"I00192","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1869,"month":8,"day":24,"city":"London","state":"Ontario","country":"Canada"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1915,"month":3,"day":19,"city":"Manhattan","county":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM112","plot_notes":"Woodlawn Cemetery, Bronx NY. FindAGrave confirms."},"residence":{"city":"Manhattan","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_sp